  <h1>Freelance vs. Employee: The True Cost Comparison</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Phoenix Reyes (PR), Independent Contractor (10+ yrs), Freelance Pricing Lead.</em></p>

  <h2>Why the Comparison Is Misleading If You Do It Wrong</h2>
  <p>When someone is deciding whether to go freelance, or when a freelancer is wondering if their rates are competitive with employment, the most common mistake is a direct salary comparison: "I made $80,000 as an employee, so if I bill $80,000 as a freelancer, I'm doing the same." This comparison ignores the enormous difference in total compensation cost between employment and self-employment.</p>
  <p>A proper comparison looks at total economic value on both sides: what the employee actually costs the employer (not just salary), and what the freelancer actually receives after paying their self-employment overhead. When you do that comparison correctly, the number a freelancer needs to charge to achieve genuine parity with an employment position is almost always substantially higher than the equivalent employee salary.</p>

  <h2>The Employee's True Total Compensation</h2>
  <p>When an employer pays an employee $80,000 in salary, that $80,000 is only part of what the employee costs. The total employer cost typically includes:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Base salary:</strong> $80,000</li>
    <li><strong>Employer payroll taxes (FICA):</strong> 7.65% × $80,000 = $6,120</li>
    <li><strong>Employer health insurance contribution:</strong> $6,000–$12,000/year (varies widely by plan and employer)</li>
    <li><strong>Employer 401(k) match:</strong> Commonly 3–6% of salary = $2,400–$4,800</li>
    <li><strong>Employer life/disability insurance contribution:</strong> $1,000–$2,000</li>
    <li><strong>Paid time off (vacation, sick, holidays):</strong> ~3 weeks = approximately $4,600 of salary cost with no corresponding work output</li>
    <li><strong>Workers' comp insurance, unemployment insurance:</strong> 1–3% of payroll</li>
    <li><strong>Office space, equipment, software allocated to the employee</strong></li>
  </ul>
  <p>Total employer cost for an $80,000 salary employee is typically $95,000–$115,000 or more. This is the number a freelancer must match in gross billings to provide equivalent value to a client — and the floor rate for parity with employment from the freelancer's own perspective.</p>

  <h2>The Freelancer's True Net Income</h2>
  <p>Now look at the same from the freelancer's side. If a freelancer bills $80,000 in a year, here's what they actually keep:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Gross billings:</strong> $80,000</li>
    <li><strong>Less: Self-employment tax (15.3%):</strong> ~$11,304 (reduced slightly by the deductible half)</li>
    <li><strong>Less: Health insurance premiums:</strong> $6,000–$15,000 (individual to family coverage)</li>
    <li><strong>Less: Retirement contributions (10% of gross):</strong> $8,000</li>
    <li><strong>Less: Business overhead (tools, insurance, accounting, marketing):</strong> $5,000–$10,000</li>
    <li><strong>Less: Federal income tax on remaining income:</strong> $6,000–$10,000</li>
    <li><strong>Less: State income tax:</strong> $0–$7,000 depending on state</li>
    <li><strong>Net take-home:</strong> approximately $30,000–$44,000</li>
  </ul>
  <p>That same $80,000 employee, meanwhile, keeps approximately $54,000–$62,000 after federal and state income tax (but before any 401(k) contributions and with employer-provided health insurance already in their pocket). The freelancer is leaving more than $20,000 on the table by billing the same gross amount as an equivalent employee salary.</p>

  <h2>What Rate Achieves True Parity?</h2>
  <p>Using the same $80,000 salary example and conservative assumptions, a freelancer needs to bill approximately $120,000–$140,000 in gross revenue to achieve genuine economic parity with an $80,000 salaried employee — accounting for SE tax, benefits, overhead, and reasonable retirement savings. That's a 50–75% premium over the equivalent employee salary. This is not gouging; it's accurately pricing the transfer of employment costs from the employer to the freelancer.</p>

  <h2>Where Freelancing Has a Real Financial Advantage</h2>
  <p>The comparison above isn't meant to discourage freelancing — it's meant to ensure freelancers price it correctly. When priced correctly, freelancing has genuine financial advantages:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>No income ceiling from a single employer:</strong> A freelancer can add clients, raise rates, or expand into adjacent services without waiting for an employer to approve a raise or promotion.</li>
    <li><strong>Tax deduction advantages:</strong> Self-employed individuals have access to deductions employees don't — home office, vehicle business use, retirement plans (SEP-IRA, Solo 401k) with higher contribution limits than employee plans, health insurance deduction on the front page of the return.</li>
    <li><strong>QBI deduction:</strong> The 20% Qualified Business Income deduction (IRC Section 199A) can significantly reduce taxable income for many self-employed individuals.</li>
    <li><strong>Flexibility and autonomy:</strong> These have real economic value that doesn't show up in a tax analysis but is very real to the people who have it.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The Tax-Equivalent Rate Calculation</h2>
  <p>A useful practical exercise: use FreelancePricingCalc to calculate the gross hourly rate that would give you the same after-tax, after-costs take-home income as your current (or comparable) employee position. That rate is your "tax-equivalent rate" — the minimum at which freelancing is financially competitive with employment. Position your actual rate above that floor to account for the income variability and career risk premium that self-employment carries.</p>
  <p>Most freelancers who run this calculation for the first time discover their current rates are below their tax-equivalent rate — which explains why freelancing feels financially precarious even when they're busy. The fix is not to work harder; it's to charge more.</p>

